The article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring April 19, 2010, as the National Day of Service and Remembrance for Victims and Survivors of Terrorism. The proclamation recognizes the victims of terrorism both domestically and internationally and honors the heroes who have supported them. It highlights the Oklahoma City bombing in 1995 and the September 11 attacks in 2001 as examples of terrorist acts that resulted in the loss of many lives. The proclamation condemns terrorism and emphasizes the importance of unity, courage, love, faith, and commitment in the face of tragedy. It calls upon all Americans to observe the day with appropriate ceremonies, activities, and acts of community service to remember the victims and survivors of terrorism worldwide.